00:07:52,077 --> 00:07:55,938
at the center of that diagram, is giving our guests a role.

166
00:07:55,938 --> 00:07:57,839
Making sure that we are very clear about the role

167
00:07:57,839 --> 00:07:59,179
that we're giving you.

168
00:07:59,179 --> 00:08:00,660
In that original attraction, we never

169
00:08:00,660 --> 00:08:02,481
told you that you were going to be Snow White.

170
00:08:02,481 --> 00:08:03,921
And so of course, you expected to see her.

171
00:08:03,921 --> 00:08:05,142
You did not know who you were.

172
00:08:05,142 --> 00:08:08,143
And by the way, being a camera is not necessarily a role.

173
00:08:08,143 --> 00:08:10,103
That doesn't really feel like you're a part of that world.

174
00:08:10,800 --> 00:08:14,082
Moreover, it's important that we give you a role that fits.

175
00:08:14,082 --> 00:08:17,225
It can be really difficult to empathize with a character

176
00:08:17,225 --> 00:08:18,746
whose story you already know.

177
00:08:18,746 --> 00:08:20,788
Snow White has already made her decisions.

178
00:08:20,788 --> 00:08:22,049
Her story has already unfolded.

179
00:08:22,049 --> 00:08:23,270
We know how it plays out.

180
00:08:23,270 --> 00:08:24,330
Mine is just beginning.

181
00:08:24,330 --> 00:08:26,732
So you don't necessarily want to be in the role of a main

182
00:08:26,732 --> 00:08:28,514
character, and you don't necessarily want to hand

183
00:08:28,514 --> 00:08:30,956
somebody a back story that they don't know, relationships

184
00:08:30,956 --> 00:08:34,378
with characters that they can't identify with, goals

185
00:08:34,378 --> 00:08:35,419
that don't resonate with them.

186
00:08:35,419 --> 00:08:37,981
You need to meet guests where they are and give

187
00:08:37,981 --> 00:08:39,322
them a role that fits.

188
00:08:39,777 --> 00:08:42,279
So let's look at an example from opening day Disneyland

