00:11:47,868 --> 00:11:49,549
something that I get to,

256
00:11:49,549 --> 00:11:52,531
and maybe even something that I get to do.

257
00:11:52,531 --> 00:11:55,614
So we have all of that.

258
00:11:55,614 --> 00:11:56,194
Where am I going?

259
00:11:57,580 --> 00:12:02,843
Well, so as we create our worlds, as we bring the worlds of the film to life, now that you

260
00:12:02,843 --> 00:12:06,064
have a role, we want you to inhabit a living world.

261
00:12:06,064 --> 00:12:11,787
When you see Snow White in that frame, for example, she is able to not walk through a

262
00:12:11,787 --> 00:12:12,508
static world.

263
00:12:12,508 --> 00:12:14,489
Static worlds are creepy worlds.

264
00:12:14,489 --> 00:12:17,170
Even the haunted mansion, which is full of dead people, moves.

265
00:12:18,191 --> 00:12:21,673
In horror movies, when things are static, that's how you know that things are about

266
00:12:21,673 --> 00:12:22,873
to get really, really scary.

267
00:12:22,873 --> 00:12:27,756
And so when we bring these worlds to life, we want to create living worlds, breathing

268
00:12:27,756 --> 00:12:28,636
worlds, worlds that move.

269
00:12:28,636 --> 00:12:32,859
And obviously, Walt and those original Imagineers with a background in animation,

270
00:12:33,599 --> 00:12:34,640
were passionate about that.

271
00:12:34,640 --> 00:12:36,883
And so Walt at the time was very intrigued

272
00:12:36,883 --> 00:12:38,725
by these little mechanical birds.

273
00:12:38,725 --> 00:12:39,986
He had found a couple of these

274
00:12:39,986 --> 00:12:41,888
and actually started a small collection.

275
00:12:41,888 --> 00:12:44,792
And these birds, these little mechanical birds,

276
00:12:44,792 --> 00:12:46,053
held the illusion of life,

277
00:12:46,053 --> 00:12:48,676
that same concept that they had in their film animation.

278
00:12:49,777 --> 00:12:52,039
They were seeing play out in 3D space.

279
00:12:52,039 --> 00:12:54,181
And this became a trend in imagining.

280
00:12:54,181 --> 00:12:56,343
This became a cornerstone for us,

281
00:12:56,343 --> 00:12:58,385
this idea of audio animatronics.

282
00:12:58,385 --> 00:13:01,548
And using that illusion of life in three dimensions

283
00:13:01,548 --> 00:13:04,151
to bring our stories to life in new ways.

284
00:13:04,151 --> 00:13:05,933
And this is just a couple brief clips

285
00:13:05,933 --> 00:13:07,474
of some of the highlights.

286
00:13:07,614 --> 00:13:09,496
That one right there, Lincoln standing up,

287
00:13:09,496 --> 00:13:11,898
that was sort of a seminal moment in audio animatronics.

288
00:13:11,898 --> 00:13:14,340
Up until that moment, the animatronics

289
00:13:14,340 --> 00:13:16,201
were very stiff, very stationary.

290
00:13:16,201 --> 00:13:18,043
Everyone thought that Abe was just

291
00:13:18,043 --> 00:13:21,245
going to be sitting there in that chair, all nice

292
00:13:21,245 --> 00:13:21,966
and peaceful.

293
00:13:21,966 --> 00:13:23,427
And then he goes and he stands up.

294
00:13:23,427 --> 00:13:27,050
He becomes more lifelike than anyone had expected him to be.

295
00:13:27,890 --> 00:13:29,691
And we continue to push the envelope here, right?

296
00:13:29,691 --> 00:13:32,273
This is really key to bringing our worlds to life.

297
00:13:32,273 --> 00:13:34,854
This is the shaman figure from Pandora,

298
00:13:34,854 --> 00:13:37,336
the world of Avatar at Disney's Animal Kingdom.

299
00:13:37,336 --> 00:13:40,258
Now this animatronic is incredibly sophisticated.

300
00:13:40,258 --> 00:13:42,179
It contains over 140 functions in the head alone.

301
00:13:43,900 --> 00:13:46,442
to bring this character to life.

302
00:13:46,442 --> 00:13:50,446
And, you know, really the goal here is to take that same level of fidelity

303
00:13:50,446 --> 00:13:53,649
that you see in the movies, right, where special effects animators

304
00:13:53,649 --> 00:13:57,913
are able to bring these characters to life with every tool at their disposal.

305
00:13:57,913 --> 00:14:01,176
We want to give that same tool to our animators in three dimensions.

306
00:14:02,873 --> 00:14:05,476
But most of the things we've been talking about here,

307
00:14:05,476 --> 00:14:06,817
we are an audience to, right?

308
00:14:06,817 --> 00:14:08,958
These animatronics are putting on a show,

309
00:14:08,958 --> 00:14:11,120
whether that's the Tiki Room, whether that's Mr. Lincoln,

310
00:14:11,120 --> 00:14:12,861
even the shaman as you go floating by.

311
00:14:12,861 --> 00:14:16,504
These are things where we become silent observers for that.

312
00:14:16,504 --> 00:14:18,346
That's not Snow White's experience at all.

313
00:14:19,370 --> 00:14:22,894
She's in a world where as she moves through it,

314
00:14:22,894 --> 00:14:24,616
that world reacts to her presence.

315
00:14:24,616 --> 00:14:27,840
That's how we know that she's in that world.

316
00:14:27,840 --> 00:14:31,104
And so to do that, we started asking the question,

317
00:14:31,104 --> 00:14:33,787
can we make that illusion of life responsive?

318
00:14:33,787 --> 00:14:36,010
Can we make that world respond to what you do?

319
00:14:36,771 --> 00:14:38,873
So going back to the collector's collection,

320
00:14:38,873 --> 00:14:41,395
as you're going to Guardians of the Galaxy mission breakout,

321
00:14:41,395 --> 00:14:45,338
you go through, you get to see a little bit of the collection.

322
00:14:45,338 --> 00:14:47,940
And in that collection, there are

323
00:14:47,940 --> 00:14:50,903
some creatures from around the galaxy,

324
00:14:50,903 --> 00:14:53,465
including these little Vilew.

325
00:14:53,465 --> 00:14:54,846
And these guys.

326
00:14:56,381 --> 00:14:58,982
actually react to our guests.

327
00:14:58,982 --> 00:15:02,602
So they're packed with a bunch of sensors.

328
00:15:02,602 --> 00:15:06,383
And as guests are going by, they're looking for big gestures.

329
00:15:06,383 --> 00:15:07,844
They're looking for your gestures.

330
00:15:07,844 --> 00:15:09,564
They're looking for their sounds.

331
00:15:09,564 --> 00:15:14,025
And just like a creature is taking in information

332
00:15:14,025 --> 00:15:19,046
from the world and then reacting to it, they do that.

333
00:15:19,046 --> 00:15:21,787
And they have a personality.

334
00:15:21,787 --> 00:15:23,867
So the idea that, well,

335
00:15:24,740 --> 00:15:27,181
Somebody who's making big motions,

336
00:15:27,181 --> 00:15:29,642
that's a little scary.

337
00:15:29,642 --> 00:15:31,643
But another Vailou who's a little more brave

338
00:15:31,643 --> 00:15:33,803
is gonna lean in and just be really curious.

339
00:15:33,803 --> 00:15:37,105
So each of them have their own personality

340
00:15:37,105 --> 00:15:38,465
and react to you.

341
00:15:38,465 --> 00:15:40,986
And what's really amazing about that happening

342
00:15:40,986 --> 00:15:44,107
is that that role that we gave you earlier

343
00:15:44,107 --> 00:15:48,349
as first as a visitor and then as an accomplice,

344
00:15:48,349 --> 00:15:50,009
it makes you real in the world.

345
00:15:50,009 --> 00:15:52,950
That if the world changes because of things that you do,

346
00:15:53,750 --> 00:15:59,772
that world becomes more real and you become more real within that world.

347
00:15:59,772 --> 00:16:07,633
So when you think about it, if you remove all of the movement from a world,

348
00:16:07,633 --> 00:16:11,294
that's actually how horror movies start.

349
00:16:11,294 --> 00:16:13,214
That's how you know something's wrong.

350
00:16:13,214 --> 00:16:16,255
It feels dead. It feels creepy.

351
00:16:16,255 --> 00:16:18,695
Even the ghosts in the Haunted Mansion move.

352
00:16:19,315 --> 00:16:22,997
the feeling of a static world, it feels dead.

353
00:16:22,997 --> 00:16:24,918
So how do we make it move?

354
00:16:24,918 --> 00:16:28,220
How do we make, and making that responsiveness

355
00:16:28,220 --> 00:16:31,862
actually validates the existence of that person

356
00:16:31,862 --> 00:16:33,443
in the role that they're playing.

357
00:16:33,443 --> 00:16:35,344
So as we bring the environment to life,

358
00:16:35,344 --> 00:16:38,065
we're making that role that you're playing

359
00:16:38,065 --> 00:16:40,586
even more deep and meaningful inside of that world.

360
00:16:43,628 --> 00:16:45,810
So we're playing a meaningful role.

361
00:16:45,810 --> 00:16:47,071
The world is responding to us.

362
00:16:47,071 --> 00:16:49,433
Now we're actually not feeling like an extra.

363
00:16:49,433 --> 00:16:52,115
We're beginning to feel like a protagonist in this story.

364
00:16:52,115 --> 00:16:53,777
And what do protagonists do?

365
00:16:53,777 --> 00:16:57,500
Well, they take action that moves the story forward.

366
00:16:57,500 --> 00:16:58,841
And so one of the really important things

367
00:16:58,841 --> 00:17:00,943
here is to look for a way that our guests can actually

368
00:17:00,943 --> 00:17:03,985
propel the narrative, that their action can

369
00:17:03,985 --> 00:17:06,488
be the impetus for the story continuing.

370
00:17:06,888 --> 00:17:09,611
Now, this is something, again, we're here at GDC.

371
00:17:09,611 --> 00:17:13,154
You guys know all about the importance of players or guests

372
00:17:13,154 --> 00:17:14,495
taking action, right?

373
00:17:14,495 --> 00:17:16,678
Action is the foundation of play.

374
00:17:16,678 --> 00:17:19,080
It's the foundation of challenge.

375
00:17:19,080 --> 00:17:21,783
It's the foundation of so many of these things.

376
00:17:21,783 --> 00:17:24,866
But it turns out that when you go and try and take play,

377
00:17:24,866 --> 00:17:26,427
which people already do in their living

378
00:17:26,427 --> 00:17:29,190
rooms with their families, and bring it into the real world,

379
00:17:29,190 --> 00:17:30,231
you encounter some challenges.

380
00:17:31,114 --> 00:17:33,976
And so for example, when I'm at home with my wife,

381
00:17:33,976 --> 00:17:36,198
my six-year-old, we're playing a board game,

382
00:17:36,198 --> 00:17:38,779
I will do ridiculous things that I would not

383
00:17:38,779 --> 00:17:40,220
do in the supermarket.

384
00:17:40,220 --> 00:17:42,702
When I am playing online with my friends,

385
00:17:42,702 --> 00:17:44,523
I will put my avatar into an outfit

386
00:17:44,523 --> 00:17:47,245
that I would not feel comfortable wearing here at GDC.

387
00:17:47,245 --> 00:17:49,426
There are things that you do that

388
00:17:49,426 --> 00:17:52,228
are ridiculous among friends and in the privacy of your home

389
00:17:52,228 --> 00:17:55,330
that you would not do in a public space.

390
00:17:55,330 --> 00:17:56,631
And so really, the question here is,

391
00:17:56,631 --> 00:17:59,673
how do we encourage guests to play in public the same way

392
00:17:59,673 --> 00:18:00,654
that they would play at home?

393
00:18:01,381 --> 00:18:05,783
Or to put it differently, how do we get a normal teenager to wear a silly hat?

394
00:18:05,783 --> 00:18:08,504
How do we go about crossing that divide?

395
00:18:08,504 --> 00:18:14,327
And it turns out that the answer is something that's familiar to most of you guys in the game design industry,

396
00:18:14,327 --> 00:18:15,288
which is you make a magic circle.

397
00:18:16,028 --> 00:18:21,412
Now, this term was popularized in game design, and essentially, you know, it's that concept

398
00:18:21,412 --> 00:18:26,295
of leaving the real world behind, right, setting aside the rules of everyday life and reality,

399
00:18:26,295 --> 00:18:32,660
and substituting them with the reality of a game, right, with a new context of the game.

400
00:18:32,660 --> 00:18:36,122
Now, the Imagineers back in 1952, you know, 1955 when the park opened.

401
00:18:37,343 --> 00:18:39,925
wouldn't have been familiar with the term magic circle,

402
00:18:39,925 --> 00:18:43,787
and yet they built a literal magic circle around the park.

403
00:18:43,787 --> 00:18:45,788
At Disneyland, we actually have a train

404
00:18:45,788 --> 00:18:48,230
that encircles the entire park that's elevated

405
00:18:48,230 --> 00:18:51,792
so you cannot see the real world from inside of the park.

406
00:18:51,792 --> 00:18:52,993
We call it the berm.

407
00:18:52,993 --> 00:18:55,815
And actually, at the entrance to this park,

408
00:18:55,815 --> 00:18:58,977
as you cross underneath that train track,

409
00:18:58,977 --> 00:19:00,978
there's a plaque that explicitly states,

410
00:19:00,978 --> 00:19:03,100
here you leave the real world behind

411
00:19:03,100 --> 00:19:04,621
and enter a world of fantasy.

412
00:19:05,441 --> 00:19:07,842
And so that's actually the trick.

413
00:19:07,842 --> 00:19:10,223
It turns out that we're not asking you to play

414
00:19:10,223 --> 00:19:11,343
in the real world.

415
00:19:11,343 --> 00:19:14,584
We're giving you an alibi to play in a fantasy world.

416
00:19:14,584 --> 00:19:16,325
We're creating a fantasy world

417
00:19:16,325 --> 00:19:18,486
that happens to exist in real space.

418
00:19:18,486 --> 00:19:21,227
And when you do that, it gives you permission to play.

419
00:19:21,227 --> 00:19:22,587
It gives you permission to act.

420
00:19:22,587 --> 00:19:25,909
It gives you permission to experiment and to role play

421
00:19:25,909 --> 00:19:29,390
in a way that you may not do out in public spaces,

422
00:19:29,390 --> 00:19:30,710
and yet you will do here at Disneyland.

423
00:19:30,710 --> 00:19:32,131
And we see this all the time.

424
00:19:32,631 --> 00:19:34,492
And we've taken advantage of this

425
00:19:34,492 --> 00:19:36,773
by creating a lot of experiences that

426
00:19:36,773 --> 00:19:39,715
allow you to take a deeper part in the story

427
00:19:39,715 --> 00:19:41,816
and really move the story forward.

428
00:19:41,816 --> 00:19:45,779
So one example of this is Agent P's World Showcase Adventure

429
00:19:45,779 --> 00:19:47,720
that is out in Epcot in Florida.

430
00:19:47,720 --> 00:19:49,841
Now, this was actually designed.

431
00:19:49,841 --> 00:19:50,982
He might be here in the audience.

432
00:19:50,982 --> 00:19:52,583
Is Jonathan Ackley out there right now?

433
00:19:54,458 --> 00:19:56,301
If he's raising his hand, I can't tell.

434
00:19:56,301 --> 00:19:58,745
But one of our Imagineers here at the conference

435
00:19:58,745 --> 00:20:00,327
actually designed these games, had

436
00:20:00,327 --> 00:20:02,471
been creating adventure games for home platforms

437
00:20:02,471 --> 00:20:04,794
for a long time, and actually came to Imagineering

438
00:20:04,794 --> 00:20:06,357
and created a series of adventure games

439
00:20:06,357 --> 00:20:08,600
that play out in physical space.

440
00:20:08,881 --> 00:20:11,303
And these allow you to explore the environment,

441
00:20:11,303 --> 00:20:13,366
just like you would in a traditional adventure game.

442
00:20:13,366 --> 00:20:15,107
But instead of pointing and clicking,

443
00:20:15,107 --> 00:20:18,111
you're actually physically moving through the space.

444
00:20:18,111 --> 00:20:19,212
Now, in order to understand this video,

445
00:20:19,212 --> 00:20:20,513
you have to go back to a time

446
00:20:20,513 --> 00:20:23,537
when we didn't all carry smartphones in our pocket.

447
00:20:23,537 --> 00:20:25,559
We actually used to hand out flip phones

448
00:20:25,559 --> 00:20:28,322
for this experience so that people could have it.

449
00:20:28,322 --> 00:20:29,824
But as you're moving through the park.

450
00:20:30,544 --> 00:20:32,285
You are receiving missions.

451
00:20:32,285 --> 00:20:34,646
You are receiving treasure hunts, scavenger hunts,

452
00:20:34,646 --> 00:20:38,308
that allow you to find and trigger magic in the environment.

453
00:20:38,308 --> 00:20:40,129
You interact with physical props.

454
00:20:40,129 --> 00:20:41,449
You deploy satellite dishes.

455
00:20:41,449 --> 00:20:43,811
You receive encoded messages.

456
00:20:43,811 --> 00:20:45,311
You interact with cast members.

457
00:20:45,311 --> 00:20:47,072
You interact with all sorts of things.

458
00:20:47,072 --> 00:20:48,033
And it turns out...

459
00:20:48,573 --> 00:20:52,776
that while the mechanics are very similar to playing an adventure game at home,

460
00:20:52,776 --> 00:20:56,199
there's something very different that happens when it plays out in the real world.

461
00:20:56,199 --> 00:20:59,261
We're all very used to having agency in a world of pixels.

462
00:20:59,261 --> 00:21:03,184
It's very different to have agency in a world of bricks and mortar.

463
00:21:03,184 --> 00:21:07,508
To actually change the physical environment around you at the push of a digital button

464
00:21:07,508 --> 00:21:08,949
is still very magical, right?

465
00:21:08,949 --> 00:21:12,411
That phone almost becomes a remote control for the entire park.

466
00:21:12,411 --> 00:21:14,653
And you're able to find magic right under your nose,

467
00:21:14,653 --> 00:21:16,415
or in the case of this troll, right under his nose.

468
00:21:16,695 --> 00:21:21,136
right, and really make things, you know, sort of magically appear.

469
00:21:21,136 --> 00:21:23,136
Now we've taken this one step farther,

470
00:21:23,136 --> 00:21:26,437
and last year we launched the Play Disney Parks app.

471
00:21:26,437 --> 00:21:29,178
And this is, again, taking that idea of agency even farther,

472
00:21:29,178 --> 00:21:33,198
where you are now able to use the entire park as a game board,

473
00:21:33,198 --> 00:21:35,599
and your phone is able to follow your lead.

474
00:21:35,599 --> 00:21:38,620
Your personal device is able to understand where you are

475
00:21:38,620 --> 00:21:41,900
and allow you to interact with the environment in unique ways,

476
00:21:41,900 --> 00:21:43,801
depending on the story world that you're within.

477
00:21:44,261 --> 00:21:48,183
And so if you take your phone to Peter Pan's flight,

478
00:21:48,183 --> 00:21:49,783
the wonderful Peter Pan adventure,

479
00:21:49,783 --> 00:21:52,484
you're able to collect pixie dust.

480
00:21:52,484 --> 00:21:54,005
You're able to find hidden objects.

481
00:21:54,005 --> 00:21:56,366
And you're able to even make Tinkerbell appear.

482
00:21:56,366 --> 00:21:57,526
If you bring that over to Space Mountain,

483
00:21:57,526 --> 00:22:00,207
you start landing spaceships and preparing for your flight

484
00:22:00,207 --> 00:22:01,388
through outer space.

485
00:22:01,388 --> 00:22:03,389
And pretty soon here, if you bring it

486
00:22:03,389 --> 00:22:04,849
to Star Wars Galaxy's Edge.

487
00:22:05,870 --> 00:22:07,851
Just as you step into that narrative,

488
00:22:07,851 --> 00:22:09,752
your device steps into that narrative, too.

489
00:22:09,752 --> 00:22:12,414
And it can become a Star Wars data pad that is, again,

490
00:22:12,414 --> 00:22:14,775
your gateway to taking action.

491
00:22:14,775 --> 00:22:17,517
You can join the Resistance and go on a mission,

492
00:22:17,517 --> 00:22:20,619
or you might decide to align yourself with the First Order

493
00:22:20,619 --> 00:22:21,800
and support their cause.

494
00:22:21,800 --> 00:22:23,021
So in all of these, the story unfolds

495
00:22:23,021 --> 00:22:26,943
because you take action.

496
00:22:26,943 --> 00:22:32,386
Because you do something, because you act,

497
00:22:32,386 --> 00:22:34,128
the world changes.

498
00:22:34,932 --> 00:22:38,436
And that's the very definition of a protagonist.

499
00:22:38,436 --> 00:22:41,119
The world, your experience of the world,

500
00:22:41,119 --> 00:22:44,082
that story does not continue unless you do something.

501
00:22:44,082 --> 00:22:47,646
Things don't happen to you, things happen because of you.

502
00:22:48,715 --> 00:22:52,057
And so we took that idea and said, all right,

503
00:22:52,057 --> 00:22:54,378
that's pretty exciting as a park.

504
00:22:54,378 --> 00:22:58,440
What happens is park overlay in these little pockets

