01:00:24,221 --> 01:00:28,647
Like, how do you know the experiences are going to be received as intended by a kid?

1258
01:00:29,665 --> 01:00:33,887
So this is in the perspective setting of literally

1259
01:00:33,887 --> 01:00:37,268
understanding what do kids see out of this experience.

1260
01:00:37,268 --> 01:00:42,110
I have been in Imagineering about a third of the time

1261
01:00:42,110 --> 01:00:42,710
that Brent has.

1262
01:00:42,710 --> 01:00:47,653
And so had the experience of, never had the experience

1263
01:00:47,653 --> 01:00:48,593
of the parks as a child.

1264
01:00:48,593 --> 01:00:51,554
A colleague said, all right.

1265
01:00:52,823 --> 01:00:53,944
We're going to judge this.

1266
01:00:53,944 --> 01:00:55,805
We're going to put you on a rolly chair,

1267
01:00:55,805 --> 01:00:57,466
and you're going to roll through this

1268
01:00:57,466 --> 01:01:02,928
and look at what does somebody who is waist high, what

1269
01:01:02,928 --> 01:01:04,729
do they understand in this world?

1270
01:01:04,729 --> 01:01:07,530
And so seeing, well.

1271
01:01:08,110 --> 01:01:11,033
Sometimes you see a lot of crowds of legs.

1272
01:01:11,033 --> 01:01:14,236
So bringing those details down to extending them

1273
01:01:14,236 --> 01:01:17,019
all the way down to the floor, understanding

1274
01:01:17,019 --> 01:01:19,801
what that experience is like.

1275
01:01:19,801 --> 01:01:24,265
I like to borrow as many families and friends

1276
01:01:24,265 --> 01:01:26,728
that I can and go to the park with them

1277
01:01:26,728 --> 01:01:30,972
to be able to understand what is their experience of going

1278
01:01:30,972 --> 01:01:31,552
to the parks.

1279
01:01:32,633 --> 01:01:37,214
So that empathy as a designer is really important

1280
01:01:37,214 --> 01:01:43,316
and it is all too easy to lose track of

1281
01:01:43,316 --> 01:01:46,337
this is the experience for me.

1282
01:01:46,337 --> 01:01:49,078
You have to play in the, we play test constantly

1283
01:01:49,078 --> 01:01:52,499
to better understand our test, our assumptions

1284
01:01:52,499 --> 01:01:55,260
about what do you understand, what do you know,

1285
01:01:55,260 --> 01:01:58,761
how do you interact, and try to look at it

1286
01:01:58,761 --> 01:02:01,842
through the eyes of our guests in all their variety.

1287
01:02:03,022 --> 01:02:03,302
Thank you.

1288
01:02:03,302 --> 01:02:03,943
Hi there.

1289
01:02:03,943 --> 01:02:06,425
Oh, I think they cut us off.

1290
01:02:06,425 --> 01:02:06,585
Hello.

1291
01:02:06,585 --> 01:02:14,034
Oh, in the case of a lot of my favorite games, I had to lose a lot before I could win.

1292
01:02:14,034 --> 01:02:20,340
Do you think it's possible to have a satisfying theme park attraction that actually ends in

1293
01:02:20,340 --> 01:02:21,281
loss or failure?

1294
01:02:22,356 --> 01:02:27,603
Yeah, well, you know, yes.

1295
01:02:27,603 --> 01:02:29,665
But I think that that is defined differently, right?

1296
01:02:29,665 --> 01:02:31,387
I mean, I think that we always want you to have a good time.

1297
01:02:31,387 --> 01:02:33,390
I mean, the reason that you kept playing that game

1298
01:02:33,390 --> 01:02:35,412
is not just because it was challenging,

1299
01:02:35,412 --> 01:02:37,995
but because the challenge was a fun challenge, right?

1300
01:02:38,596 --> 01:02:40,837
And I think that within the context of our parks,

1301
01:02:40,837 --> 01:02:42,778
we need to account for guests who

1302
01:02:42,778 --> 01:02:45,940
are going to be able to ride that ride hundreds of times,

1303
01:02:45,940 --> 01:02:48,321
as well as people for whom that experience might be a once

1304
01:02:48,321 --> 01:02:49,741
in a lifetime experience.

1305
01:02:49,741 --> 01:02:50,982
And so we're always looking at, how

1306
01:02:50,982 --> 01:02:53,703
do we make sure that it's fun the first time you play it?

1307
01:02:53,703 --> 01:02:56,505
And how do we make sure that it's still fun the hundredth

1308
01:02:56,505 --> 01:02:57,585
time you've gone through it?

1309
01:02:57,965 --> 01:03:01,188
And so a lot of the times we look at sort of variable success

1310
01:03:01,188 --> 01:03:04,970
more than digital decisions of failure and success.

1311
01:03:04,970 --> 01:03:07,672
An example, going back to Toy Story Mania,

1312
01:03:07,672 --> 01:03:10,574
is we have a high striker board that sort of gives you

1313
01:03:10,574 --> 01:03:13,396
your score at the end and lets you know how well you did.

1314
01:03:13,396 --> 01:03:15,297
No matter what, you get to shoot confetti out

1315
01:03:15,297 --> 01:03:16,318
of that cannon at the end.

1316
01:03:16,318 --> 01:03:18,959
It is a celebration of however well you did.

1317
01:03:18,959 --> 01:03:20,420
But you also get sort of a metric

1318
01:03:20,420 --> 01:03:22,141
of how well you did in the grand scheme of things.

1319
01:03:22,582 --> 01:03:25,524
And I'll give a slightly humbling example there.

1320
01:03:25,524 --> 01:03:27,525
I was part of the design team on Mania,

1321
01:03:27,525 --> 01:03:31,607
and I rode that ride hundreds of times before it opened.

1322
01:03:31,607 --> 01:03:32,568
It was a tough job.

1323
01:03:32,568 --> 01:03:34,869
And me and the other designers had a little bit

1324
01:03:34,869 --> 01:03:36,470
of a running competition going on.

1325
01:03:36,470 --> 01:03:38,912
I think my personal high score that I ever got

1326
01:03:38,912 --> 01:03:42,694
was about 380,000 points, which we thought was,

1327
01:03:42,694 --> 01:03:44,616
I thought was pretty dang good.

1328
01:03:44,616 --> 01:03:47,958
We opened up, and within a couple months of opening,

1329
01:03:47,958 --> 01:03:49,799
we had annual pass holders who had already crossed

1330
01:03:49,799 --> 01:03:50,119
the 500,000 mark.

1331
01:03:51,340 --> 01:03:55,767
And so no matter how deep you make it, people will go deeper.

1332
01:03:55,767 --> 01:03:58,452
But it still needs to be fun that first time through.

1333
01:03:58,452 --> 01:03:59,934
And that's always what we're trying to balance.

1334
01:03:59,934 --> 01:04:00,154
Thank you.

